3.2 File Name Completion
========================

Type ‘@’ followed by a partial file path to trigger file name completion
in the prompt buffer.  The completion backend is controlled by
‘pi-file-completion-backend’.


File: pi.info,  Node: Bash,  Next: Sending Context,  Prev: File Name Completion,  Up: Usage

3.3 Bash
========

Prefix a command with ‘!’ to run it in Bash.  Use ‘!!’ to run a command
without adding it to the conversation context.

     ! echo "hello"


File: pi.info,  Node: Sending Context,  Next: Images,  Prev: Bash,  Up: Usage

3.4 Sending Context
===================

You can send contextual information from any buffer to the Pi chat
prompt.

Command                   Description
--------------------------------------------------------------------------
‘pi-send-region’          Append the selected region to the prompt
                          input.
‘pi-send-filename’        Append the current buffer's filename
                          (prefixed with ‘@’) to the prompt input.
‘pi-send-flycheck-errors’ Append the Flycheck errors at point to the
                          prompt input.  Falls back to all current
                          errors in the buffer when there are none at
                          point.


File: pi.info,  Node: Images,  Prev: Sending Context,  Up: Usage

3.5 Images
==========

You can attach images to your prompt to provide visual context to the
agent.  Images are displayed as thumbnail previews above the prompt
input area and are sent along with your message.  The agent may also
render images inline in its responses, for example when using the ‘read’
tool on a file that contains images.

3.5.1 Supported Formats
-----------------------

The following image formats are supported:

   • PNG
   • JPEG
   • GIF
   • WebP

   Drag an image file from your file manager and drop it into the Pi
chat buffer, or paste a supported image from the clipboard via
‘yank-media’.  To remove an attached image, click on the thumbnail with
the mouse, or place point on it and press ‘backspace’ or ‘delete’.


